<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-elementary-matrices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Elementary matrices</title>

 <definition xml:id="def-elementary-matrices">
<statement>
<p>
An <term>elementary matrix</term> is any matrix that can be obtained by performing a single
elementary row operation an an identity matrix.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="ex-basic-elem-matrices">
<statement>
<p>
<ul>
  <li>
  <p> <m>\begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\1 \amp 0\amp 0\\0\amp 0\amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>
  is obtained from the ERO <m>R_1\leftrightarrow R_2</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p> <m>\begin{bmatrix}4 \amp 0 \amp 0\\0 \amp 1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>
  is obtained from the ERO <m>R_1\to 4R_1</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p> <m>\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\0 \amp 1\amp 0\\0\amp -2\amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>
  is obtained from the ERO <m>R_3\to R_3- 2R_2</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
</ul>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
We need to main results about elementary matrices. We present them without proof, although 
we will illustrate the first result with an example, and it is not too hard to see 
how the first result implies the second. 
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-elem-matrices-and-multiplication">
<statement>
<p>
If <m>E</m> is an elementary matrix obtained by performing an ERO on <m>I_n</m>, then if 
the same ERO is performed on an <m>n\times p</m> matrix <m>A</m>, the result is 
the product <m>EA</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<theorem xml:id="thm-elem-matrices-invertible">
<statement>
<p>
Every elementary matrix is invertible, and the inverse is the elementary matrix 
for the 'reverse' ERO.
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<p>
By 'reverse' ERO we mean that will undo the original, sending the matrix back to the 
identity. So we have the following:
<table xml:id="tab-reverse-EROs">
  <caption>Reverse EROs</caption>
  <tabular halign="center">
    <col/>
    <col left="solid"/>
    <col left="solid"/>

    <row header="yes">
      <cell>ERO</cell>
      <cell>Reverse ERO</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell><m>R_i\leftrightarrow R_j</m></cell>
      <cell><m>R_i\leftrightarrow R_j</m></cell>
    </row>

     <row>
      <cell><m>R_i\to cR_i</m></cell>
      <cell><m>R_i\to \frac{1}{c}R_i</m></cell>
    </row>
    
     <row>
      <cell><m>R_i\to R_i+cR_j</m></cell>
      <cell><m>R_i\to R_i-cR_j</m></cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
</table>
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-checking-elem-prop">
<statement>
<p>
Consider <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}2\amp 1\\-1\amp 1\\1\amp 5\end{bmatrix}</m> and the 
ERO <m>R_3\to R_3-2R_2</m>. We check that 
<xref ref="thm-elem-matrices-and-multiplication"/> holds with this example:
<ul>
  <li>
  <p> <m>A\xrightarrow{R_3\to R_3-2R_1}\begin{bmatrix}2\amp 1\\-1\amp 1\\3\amp 3\end{bmatrix}</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p> <m>E=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 0\\0\amp -2\amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m> and 
  <md>
  EA=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 0\\0\amp -2\amp 1\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}2\amp 1\\-1\amp 1\\1\amp 5\end{bmatrix}
  =\begin{bmatrix}2\amp 1\\-1\amp 1\\3\amp 3\end{bmatrix}
  </md>.
  </p>
  </li>
</ul>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-">
<statement>
<p>
We want to express <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 3\\0\amp 3\end{bmatrix}</m> as a product 
of elementary matrices. We do this by row reducing <m>A</m> to the identity:
<md>
A=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 3\\0\amp 3\end{bmatrix}\xrightarrow{R_2\to\frac{1}{3}R_2}
\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 3\\0\amp 3\end{bmatrix}
\xrightarrow{R_1\to R_1-3R_2}\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp 1\end{bmatrix}.
</md>
We now take the corresponding elementary matrices
<md>
E_1=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp \frac{1}{3}\end{bmatrix}\text{ and }
E_2=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp -3\\0\amp 1\end{bmatrix},
</md>
and use <xref ref="thm-elem-matrices-and-multiplication"/> to get <m>E_2(E_1A)=I_2</m>. We can now 
rearrange to get <m>A=E_1^{-1}E_2^{-1}</m>. So
<md>
A=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp 3\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 3\\0\amp 1\end{bmatrix}
</md>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

</section>